{Speech 16}{}{The scorching sun stood at its zenith as I finished butchering this damned leg, carefully separating the kneecap. The guy must have done a lot of running, given all that muscle - even my knife, my "John Locke," couldn't get through this bundle. I brought in the axe, and within a couple of minutes I had beautiful, juicy human hams. To think that not long ago their owner was tearing around on his Highwayman, and now he's become my food for the coming week. This is the second day I've spent butchering - drying the body, draining the blood, gutting the entrails - it all takes patience, but now my work is done. What's more, the cauldron of torso soup was already coming to a boil. I took it off the fire, replacing it with a baking tray of chopped-up arms and legs. Pouring the soup into a mug, I took shelter from the scorching sun in the shade of the gully, and, glancing at the roasting delicacies, began to think about what to do next. I have enough food for a week, which means I can use the old trick - put up a false signpost by the abandoned road and set an ambush for overly curious travelers. I had a dozen .223 rounds, which in my case means ten victims for my trusty sniper rifle. Roasted hearts, sizzling liver... The divine taste of human flesh... Yes, time to pack up and head to Death Valley - the continuation of the hunt awaits.\nInsane }
