{Speech 17}{}{Deep night. The howling of dogs in the distance. Klamath ablaze. The Patriarch's residence is crumbling, and millions of sparks begin to swirl in the air. All around lie the corpses of the townsfolk and their "defenders," the town is filled with the smell of death and the pleasant, steady crackle of flames. But suddenly, by the knights' headquarters, a crying rings out, shattering the whole symphony. A little girl, about 10, kneels beside the corpse of some sorry cowboy and sobs hysterically. She heard my steps, raised her head... Seems she recognized me, and now she looks at me with hope. Hope is a feeling for the weak, bitch, and the weak don't survive in this world. I won't waste bullets, there's still a little gasoline left in my canister. Fear keeps her rooted to the spot, I grab the girl by the hair and lead her to the defiled well, where I unhurriedly douse her with fuel from head to toe. She screws her eyes shut and parts her lips slightly, her breathing has almost stopped, while her heart pounds wildly. I light a cigarette and toss the burning match toward my little one. For a while I watch as the fire devours her young body and savor the desperate childish shrieking. Then I kick her down into the well and stride off to the hunting grounds, where the boys in the Hummer have long been waiting for me. I climb into the off-roader and flick the cigarette out the window. We drive off toward the base, and the glow of Klamath begins to slowly recede. A beautiful sight.\n\nBoxifag }
