{Speech 20}{}{Log 1 The Beginning.\n\nThe screen lights up. You see an unshaven man surrounded by 4-5 people behind him with big guns. It looks like the recording is being made from someone's helmet.\n\n- And you want about 6 assault rifles for this rust bucket? \n- If you don't like it, you can go ask the nearest squad of crazed mutants for one just like it…\n\nBig guns, ah, I was always drawn to Big guns. Life in the wasteland is always danger, and what could be a better argument for being given a wide berth than a six-barreled monster cradled in your bare hands? \n\nI was born into a hermit's family, my mother was once a successful caravaneer, from them I probably inherited such a passion for solitude, and for haggling at length with every trader over every trifle before a purchase. \n\nBut no one is eternal, sooner or later you have to leave the walls you've grown used to.\n}
{Speech 20 Answer 21}{}{Next log}
{Speech 21}{}{\nLog 2 Wasteland.\n\n- The mark of a good trader is that he knows when to stop driving up the price.\n- Well, kid, then you've stumbled onto the wrong caravan.\n\nKlamath, a good town. I roamed this corner of America for a long time, signed up with the local militia squad, where they issued me my machine gun. I don't stay in town for long - all that crowd makes me nervous. I escort the local traders from town to town, provisions and ammunition always with me, routine…}
{Speech 21 Answer 22}{}{Next log}
{Speech 22}{}{\nLog 3 Hubologists.\n\nI learned about this project from some crazy guy who just couldn't shut up - Griza or Grido, something like that was his name. In short, the gist is eternal life through cloning, what nonsense, he himself had already been cloned more than once and seems to like it, a strange fellow. But who doesn't want to live forever?\n\nAt their base I underwent examinations and a DNA sampling. A bastion of technology. My flask is #482a. Mother of my future clones, heh. }
{Speech 22 Answer 23}{}{Next log}
{Speech 23}{}{\nLog 4 Acquaintance.\n\nEntry in the medical journal. Cloning department. The cloning tank block from 400 to 500 lost power for a couple of hours due to a strong storm on the surface, I did warn them that the solar batteries are unreliable. Run a defect analysis on the samples.\n\nThe Pit, a city of whores, junkies and bandits. Seeing someone's corpses in the streets is as ordinary as the sand. Today there are way too many of them, probably some caravan with dope got plundered, which probably drove the local junkies out of their minds. But the caravan arrived safe and sound, my job is done. I'll go have some of the local swill and back to… shhh…\nThe entry breaks off.}
{Speech 23 Answer 24}{}{Next log}
{Speech 24}{}{\nLog 5 Birth?\n\nEntry in the medical journal. Cloning department. After the power loss, a good portion of the samples were lost, ah, we ought to notify the owners before they do something stupid «smiley face». From the surviving tanks, the clones come out with mental disorders and frequent recurring temporary amnesia. But as long as they keep paying us money, I see no sense in winding down part of the project.\n\nSlime, damn slime or gel, but what's the difference. And this ringing in my ears, flickers of memory. Everything's a blur, some degenerates are jabbing knives at me, laughing. For some reason they're dragging the remains of my caravan into a pile, some of them gutted, yet still showing signs of life, looks like the maniacs find this pleasurable. The sound of fuel feeding into the mixer, a flamethrower!..}
{Speech 24 Answer 25}{}{Next log}
{Speech 25}{}{Log 6 The Past.\n\nEntry in the medical journal. Cloning department. The clones from tank #482a come into the world with congenital psychosis and persecution mania, chronic amnesia, shies away from people, behaves withdrawn during examination, conducting a dialogue is difficult. It seems he has some kind of patron, the money comes in triple, probably somewhere at the very top they forbade scrapping this tank, I don't think the subject tops up his own account. End of entry.\n\nThe first death, the only thing I remember from the past. I've already lost count of how many times I see the guys in robes, I hate the color gray.  I have to go, yes, I have to go, they're already waiting for me, they're always waiting for me, I hate them, always love to go around in a Crowd, but they have toys, I love toys, they buzz, spin and spit metal, I don't like the crowd, always these guys in gray, sick of them, I have to go, yes, I have to go.}
{Speech 25 Answer 26}{}{Next log}
{Speech 26}{}{\n\nLog 7 Home.\n\nThe familiar recording «from the helmet» lights up\n\n- Look, man, it'll just rust on you. Let's do this, I give you 5 fully loaded assault rifles, and this bag of medicines, and you give me 2 boxes of ammo and that big black cannon.\n- The medicines aren't bad, of course, weeell, alright… deal, shake on it.\n\n A mask, what is a mask, the whole wasteland wears a mask- the face they show me, the face I want to see, or the face they want me to see, traders, whores, drug dealers, the damn militia, the militia, klamath, Klamath I hate Klamath, they have my machine gun, my first machine gun, they hide it, but I'll find it, I'll kill them all, but I'll find it, I'll put on a mask, I'm kind, I'm good - they love it when I'm kind…\n\nHome, home, home. Some idiot, he's insane, there are a lot of insane ones here, there are many of them, they never go around alone, they appear when there are many of them, weaklings, I hate weaklings. They mutter something over there, they hate someone, dumb hatred, who needs it. There was a town, this idiot said my caravan was killed there, that the bastard with the flamethrower is there too, the flamethrower did I tell him about the flamethrower? I killed them. I left no one alive there, they killed too, killed and laughed, just the same way they killed me, only now I'm the one laughing.  Did I say I killed them? Damn amnesia, that's what the doctors call it, we have doctors, they don't heal, rather the opposite, why, can't tell, they're incomprehensible,  but I don't touch them, they're in white, I hate gray. The damn idiots are waiting for me for some reason, they laugh when I'm with them, but they give me weapons, it's safe with weapons, yes, safe…}
{Speech 26 Answer 27}{}{Next log}
{Speech 27}{}{\nLog 8 Habits.\n\nThe Zerg laboratory. ... and this maniac made our slaves work without rest, so that they die in droves from exhaustion, and all to pay for the replication of one defective clone. This subject is easily controlled, you just have to feed him the right thing in a certain wrapping, luckily from the Hubologists' database we know almost everything about his past. He has many obsessive thoughts, the mere mention of which literally blows his lid, and a couple of moments later he forgets what happened and what he was doing, with each replication he withdraws further into his own world, it's hard to predict what he's thinking and what he'll do the next moment, with the right gear and his skills under the right control, the perfect merciless killing machine. In a certain sense he is of interest to us, but these costs…\n\n«Congratulations on your 147th replication» - that's what they told me, the freaks in gray, again this slime, or gel, what's the difference, again the ringing in my ears, I hate this sensation. \n\nI came upon the dead, the idiots killed each other off, the last one wanted to attack me, he was one of those who wear masks, I hate those, he waved his hand at me, smiled, was in blue. But I saw through him. I beat him to death with a stone. I walked a long time, homeward, home is far, I saw a lot of people - a caravan!\n\nThey have a machine gun, and it's safe with one, luckily there are things to sell, those people are mean, I need a mask, they love masks, I hate them, I hate the crowd, they love it when I'm kind. A smile, a fake smile:\n\n- Hey, hello!\n…\n- The medicines aren't bad, of course, weeell, alright… deal, shake on it.\n\nI hate the crowd.\n\n- Thanks, safe travels.\n- Same to you, traveler.}
{Speech 27 Answer Exit}{}{[Your eyes have turned red and are bulging out of their sockets, dazed from reading such an amount of text. It seems this zerg is unusually clever, since he managed to write so many letters] Step away from the terminal.}
{Speech 28}{}{This battle was lost. \nThe lack of coordination with our allies played a cruel trick on us. The second squad, which was supposed to hit the paladins from the front, for some reason hesitated and couldn't come to our aid in time when we attacked from the flank. It was a slaughter. Pinned down in the narrow passages, we were easy targets for the rocket launchers, which threw us ever further from the avenue, not letting us advance. All of Broken Hills shuddered from the explosions, and not only from rockets. Some of our men walked right into a minefield that recon for some reason failed to report. Many stayed behind on that field…\n	 «- Well there you go, twice as many lolodins again, how are you supposed to fight like this?!», « - Damn allies, ruined everything again» - came over the radio. Everyone resigned themselves to defeat, and once again tried to find «the scapegoat».}
{Speech 28 Answer 29}{}{Next \n}
{Speech 29}{}{The whining on the radio was only a distraction. I lay on the ground, and with the last of my consciousness mentally counted down the final seconds until I would wake up in a flask of bio-solution at the special replication station. There, consciousness clears, and again it's all as always - I kick through the glass wall, tumble out, run to the door - and here I am in Hell. In the crowd of embittered replicants I scan for familiar faces - oh, I see him! A little old grandpa stands by the wall, waiting for me, or for other Zergs. He's got a tough job, not one to envy - dying a hundred times a day. But, on the other hand, it's a sin for him to complain - he'd never earn this much at any other job. Well, except maybe if he went on raids with us… But his age isn't what it used to be.\n	The grandpa, seeing me, already knows what to do. He runs at a sprint to the machine-gun turret, with a practiced motion rips the cover off the control panel and starts digging through the wires. Just don't let him mix up the sequence, the old fart. But no, the senility hasn't fully overtaken the old man yet, and a characteristic creak rings out - the turret's servomotors shut down, 12 deadly barrels point at the floor. }
{Speech 29 Answer 30}{}{Next}
{Speech 30}{}{By this moment I'm already standing on the line beyond which the «dead zone» begins - the machine guns' field of fire. As if on cue, I make a dash and run forward, toward the cherished exit.\n	Of course, I make it. So many years of training don't pass without a trace. Already rounding the corner of the corridor, I hear the rattle of machine guns and screams of agony behind me, and a smile spreads across my face. Let them pay for the replication.\n	In a torn «pajama» I run into the wasteland. It's not far to run - luckily, on one of the raids we stumbled upon an abandoned military depot, right next to the station. Now it's our base. I jump into the camouflaged hatch - I'm inside. In a hurry I dash into the depot: «Vindicator», ammo, combat armor, Psycho, super stimpaks - seems I haven't forgotten anything. I'll get dressed on the way.}
{Speech 30 Answer 31}{}{Next}
{Speech 31}{}{By the main exit a Hummer already stands with its engine running, behind the wheel sits Prophet Issa - this man usually handled all sorts of negotiations, mass-culture events and other such nonsense. But sometimes even he got sick of it all, and he would set off to vent his hatred on those with whom he had recently played football on the fields of Broken Hills. How did he lead such a «double» life? Very simply: he didn't kill with his own hands, but with the help of a combat robot, model T-800, found at some prewar base. And he himself is clean - who would suspect an old man in a robe?\n	Pedal to the floor, we tear across the wasteland. On the move I put on my combat armor - not very convenient to do in a car, I'll tell you that. The radio is tuned to our frequency, and I hear that the whining and squabbling are still going on there. Well, to hell with them, I'll knock some sense into their heads later, right now it's time to have some fun. \n	We drive right up to Broken Hills. I barely manage to tumble out of the car - Issa is already speeding off at full throttle. Well, to hell with him, at least he left that damn hunk of metal. Maybe it'll at least serve as a distraction.}
{Speech 31 Answer 32}{}{Next}
{Speech 32}{}{And in Broken Hills the paladins are already celebrating victory. Joyful cries are heard, half-naked ragamuffins - «gulls» - scurry everywhere. It would be more correct to call them «vultures» - for they feed where death has just been. Well, let them feed, today I've no time for them.\n	I make a detour and enter the city from the rear. They've surely spotted me, since you can't hide well in full gear, but the paladins evidently decided I'm a raider who got away by chance and is trying to flee. That was their mistake.\n	I burst into a house - before me are two, a guy and a girl. Their clothes - just like mine, only with the paladins' insignia. My «clients». They're chatting about something. Or rather, they were chatting, until I interrupted them by riddling the guy's back with a burst from my machine gun. No standing with your back turned when guests come into the house. The girl grabs a machine gun in horror - a Bozar, a good weapon. Probably this lover gave it to her. But there's nothing better than a Vindicator. She lets off two bursts at me - her hands are shaking, most of the bullets fly wide. Yeah, you've gone soft in your «peaceful» city, you're afraid of an ordinary death. }
{Speech 32 Answer 33}{}{Next}
{Speech 33}{}{Some of the bullets do hit me after all. One flies in between the armor plates, right into my shoulder - but I feel no pain. This stuff really is good - Psycho, you can tell at once the military made it, not those junkies from New Reno. Under the hail of shots I walk right up to the girl point-blank - and all 25 bullets fly straight to the target. Looking into her eyes, full of horror and death agony, I understand that I didn't go on this raid today for nothing. It's for moments like these that it's worth fighting.\n	I run out of the house through the back door - I see a bunch of stunned paladins. Ha, they still can't believe some madman has turned up who decided to attack a city packed to the brim with enemies. There are quite a lot of them - but out of the corner of my eye I manage to spot the T-800 on the opposite side of the street. At its feet a corpse with the characteristic insignia is already lying. Well, at least that pile of metal was good for something. \n	The paladins noticed the robot too. Taking advantage of the moment while they were deciding what to do with two enemies on different sides - I make a dash toward a small shed. Just by the wall a sniper's bullet catches up with me - no big deal, it didn't pierce the armor. In response I let off a burst - yeah, a feeble little sniper. Was.}
{Speech 33 Answer 34}{}{Next}
{Speech 34}{}{I take cover in the shed, the paladins surround me. Some brave soul runs toward me - in vain. Not many could withstand 2 point-blank bursts. And this guy is not one of them. \n	The enraged paladins charge into the attack. Yes, my fate is sealed. I knew it back when I lay here the first time. But it doesn't matter, for only by going to your death can you feel truly alive!\n	The paladins fire in bursts, hitting their own. With a final burst I finish off the wounded one who was closest to me.\n	I die with a smile on my face, thinking about how those five I'm taking with me, and two more that the T-800 riddled, will get out of Hell.\n	This battle was won.}
{Speech 34 Answer Exit}{}{With trembling knees and trepidation, step away from the terminal.}
{Speech 35}{}{Everyone went on the raid. And they left me with Vasya. Bastards. \nNo, really, just bastards. So they drank too much, so they overslept. Is it hard to wake them up? I hate it.\nVasya snoozes peacefully in the corner with his teddy bear. I'm very hungry.\nI went down to the prisoners. God, they're all so cute. Makes you want to eat them.\nAnd these funny inscriptions that Insane carved on each of their foreheads. In a word, a pedantic old kike.\nI cut off the leg of the one who had "sniper" scratched on him. The guy cursed with foul language, assured me that the rangers wouldn't let this go and would kill my dog. I wonder, who are these rangers? Anyway, what's the difference? The main thing is that the leg turned out to be quite tasty and I decided to cut myself another helping.\nBoring. \nI looked at the lab journal. In the list of planned experiments, item 12 was designated "Analysis of the sniper." I got interested.\nI fastened the legless one to the lab table, having first welded the stumps shut, took a spiked stick for analysis and began the experiment. \nHe started crying quietly and asking for his mommy, then somehow fell silent.\nWe don't give a shit about lower beings! - Suddenly a voice rang out from the sniper's direction. But I paid no attention to this shrill cackling. Let him cackle, what can you take from him? This piece of meat is not a human, and tonight a very hard night awaits him.\nEvery night was very hard for him, when he fell into our captivity, and now his anus was stretched so wide that an oil can would slide in with ease.\nJack Daniel\n}
